<section xml:id="s_separable_III" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Separable finite extensions</title>
    <theorem xml:id="th_sep_fin_ext">
        <title>Separable finite extensions</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>K/F</m> be a finite field extension of degree <m>n=[K\colon F]</m>. The following statements are equivalent. 
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <title>Separable</title>
                        
                        <p>
                            <m>K/F</m> is separable. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <title>Separably generated</title>
                        <p>
                            <m>K=F(\alpha_1,\alpha_2,\dots, \alpha_n)</m> where each <m>\alpha_i</m> is separable over <m>F</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <title>Maximal separable degree</title>
                        <p>
                            For any embedding <m>\sigma\colon F\rightarrow L</m>, with <m>L</m> algebraically closed, there are exactly <m>n=[K\colon F]</m> extensions of <m>\sigma</m> to <m>K</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </theorem>
    <proof>
        <p>
            We prove the cycle of implications (1)<m>\implies</m>(2)<m>\implies</m>(3)<m>\implies</m>(1).
        </p>
        <case>
        <title>Implication:(1)<m>\implies</m>(2)</title>
        <p>
         Assume <m>K/F</m> is finite. We have <m>K=F(\alpha_1,\alpha_2,\dots, \alpha_n)</m> for some elements <m>\alpha_i</m> by <xref ref="th_finite_ext"/>. Since <m>K/F</m> is separable, each <m>\alpha_i</m> is separable over <m>F</m>. 
        </p>
        </case>
        <case>
        <title>Implication:(2)<m>\implies</m>(3)</title>
        <p>
        Assume <m>K=F(\alpha_1,\alpha_2,\dots, \alpha_n)</m> with each <m>\alpha_i</m> separable over <m>F</m>. We show by induction on <m>n</m> that <m>K/F</m> satisfies the condition described in (3).
        </p>
        <p>
            Base case: <m>n=1</m>. In this case we have <m>K=F(\alpha)</m>. Since <m>\alpha</m> is separable over <m>F</m>, its minimal polynomial <m>f(x)=m_{\alpha,F}(x)</m> is separable. Let <m>d=\deg f</m>. Given an embedding <m>\sigma\colon F\rightarrow L</m>, where <m>L</m> is algebraically closed, we know by <xref ref="th_embed_ext_simple"/> that the set <m>X</m> of all extensions of <m>\sigma</m> to <m>K=F(\alpha)</m> is in bijective correspondence with the set <m>R</m> of all roots in <m>L</m> of the polynomial <m>f^\sigma(x)</m>. Since <m>f</m> is separable, so is <m>f^\sigma</m>. (See proof below.) Since <m>\deg f=\deg f^\sigma</m>, and since <m>f^\sigma</m> splits completely over the algebraically closed field <m>L</m>, there are <m>d</m> distinct roots of <m>f^\sigma</m>. We conclude that 
            <me>
                \abs{X}=\abs{R}=d=[F(\alpha)\colon F]
            </me>,
            as desired. 
        </p>
        <p>
             To see why <m>f^\sigma</m> is separable, let <m>\beta_1,\beta_2,\dots,\beta_d</m> be the distinct roots of <m>f</m> lying in an algebraic closure <m>\overline{F}</m>. We can extend <m>\sigma</m> to an embedding <m>\sigma^*\colon \overline{F}\rightarrow L</m> by <xref ref="th_emb_ext_alg"/>, and it is easy to see that <m>\sigma^*(\beta_i)</m> are the distinct roots of <m>f^\sigma</m>, which also has degree <m>d</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
            Induction case: let <m>n&gt; 1</m> and assume the result holds for any field extension separably generated by <m>n-1</m> elements. Given <m>K=F(\alpha_1,\alpha_2,\dots, \alpha_n)</m>, we have <m>K=K'(\alpha_n)</m>, where <m>K'=F(\alpha_1,\dots, \alpha_{n-1})</m>. Let <m>[K\colon K']=e</m> and <m>[K'\colon F]=d</m>, so that 
            <me>
                n=[K\colon F]=[K\colon K']\, [K'\colon F]=e\, d
            </me>.
            By the induction hypothesis, given any <m>\sigma\colon F\rightarrow L</m> with <m>L</m> algebraically closed, there are exactly <m>d=[K'\colon F]</m> extensions <m>\tau'\colon K'\rightarrow L</m> of <m>\sigma</m> to <m>K'</m>. Applying the base case (<m>n=1</m>) to the simple extension <m>K=K'(\alpha_n)</m>, for each such <m>\tau'\colon K'\rightarrow L</m> extending <m>\sigma</m> there are exactly <m>e=[K'(\alpha)\colon K']</m> extensions of <m>\tau'</m> to an embedding <m>\tau\colon K=K'(\alpha)\colon L</m>. We now use our <xref ref="lem_count_ext" text="custom">counting extensions of embeddings lemma</xref>. Let <m>X</m> be the set of all extensions of <m>\sigma</m> to <m>K</m>, let <m>X'</m> be the set of all extensions of <m>\sigma</m> to <m>K'</m>, and for each <m>\tau'\in X'</m>, let <m>X_{\tau'}</m> be the set of all extensions of <m>\tau'</m> to <m>K</m>. (See <xref ref="fig_cor_embed_ext_finite"/> for a visual summary of this setup.) Using <xref ref="lem_count_ext"/>, we have 
            <md>
                <mrow>\abs{X} \amp =\sum_{\tau'\in X'}\abs{X_{\tau'}}</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp =\sum_{\tau'\in X'}e \amp (\text{base step})</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = e\abs{X'}</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = ed \amp (\text{induction step})</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = n \amp (\text{tower law})</mrow>
            </md>,
            as desired. 
        </p>
        </case>
        <case>
            <title>Implication:(3)<m>\implies</m>(1)</title>
            <p>
                Assume <m>K/F</m> is finite and satisfies the condition described in (3). Let <m>\overline{F}/F</m> be an algebraic closure of <m>F</m>. Fix an <m>\alpha\in K</m>, and let <m>f(x)=m_{\alpha,F}(x)</m>. Assume <m>\deg f=d</m>. We wish to show that <m>f</m> is separable, or equivalently, that the set <m>R=\{\beta\in \overline{F}\colon f(\beta)\}</m> of roots of <m>f</m> has exactly <m>d</m> elements: <ie/>, <m>\abs{R}=d</m>. To this end, we apply condition (3) to the field embedding <m>i\colon F\rightarrow \overline{F}</m>. Namely, the set of extensions <m>X</m> of <m>i\colon F\rightarrow \overline{F}</m> to an embedding <m>\tau\colon K\rightarrow \overline{F}</m> has cardinality <m>\abs{X}=n</m>. On the other hand, we have the tower of extensions <m>K/K'/F</m>, where <m>K'=F(\alpha)</m>, and applying the <xref ref="lem_count_ext" text="custom">counting extensions of embeddings lemma</xref>, we see that 
                <md>
                    <mrow> n=\abs{X}\amp=\sum_{\tau'\in X'}X_{\tau'} </mrow>
                </md>,
                where <m>X'</m> is the set of all extensions of <m>i\colon F\rightarrow \overline{F}</m> to <m>K'=F(\alpha)</m>, and for each <m>\tau'\in X'</m>, <m>X_{\tau'}</m> is the set of all extensions of <m>\tau'</m> to <m>K</m>. (Again, see <xref ref="fig_cor_embed_ext_finite"/> for a visual summary of this setup.) Since <m>K'=F(\alpha)</m> is simple, we have <m>\abs{X'}\leq \abs{R}</m>, the number of distinct roots of <m>f</m> in <m>\overline{R}</m>, by <xref ref="th_embed_ext_simple"/>. Furthermore, for each <m>\tau'\in X'</m>, we have <m>\abs{X_{\tau'}}\leq [K\colon K']=e</m> by <xref ref="th_emb_ext_finite"/>. Thus we have 
                <md>
                    <mrow> n=\abs{X}\amp=\sum_{\tau'\in X'}X_{\tau'} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp \leq\sum_{tau'\in X'}e </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp =e\abs{X'}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp \leq e\,d</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = n</mrow>
                </md>.
                It follows that the two inequalities above are in fact equalities, and thus in particular, that <m>d=\abs{X'}=\abs{R}</m>. Thus <m>f</m> is separable, as desired. 
            </p>
            </case>
        
    </proof>
    <corollary xml:id="cor_sep_strong_trans">
        <title>Separability is strongly transitive</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>L/K/F</m> be a tower of algebraic field extensions. The extension <m>L/F</m> is separable if and only if <m>L/K</m> and <m>K/F</m> are both separable. Using logical shorthand: 
                <me>
                    L/F \text{ separable} \iff L/K \text{ separable and } K/F \text{ separable}
                </me>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </corollary>
    <corollary xml:id="cor_sep_gen">
        <title>Separable is separably generated</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
            A field extension <m>K/F</m> is separable if and only if there is a set <m>A\subseteq K</m> of separable elements such that <m>K=F(A)</m>. In plain English: an extension is separable if and only if it is separably generated. 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </corollary>
    <theorem xml:id="th_sep_prim_elem">
        <title>Primitive element theorem</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>K/F</m> be a finite separable extension. There is an element <m>\alpha\in K</m> such that <m>K=F(\alpha)</m>. Using logical shorthand: 
                <me>
                    K/F \text{ finite separable} \implies K=F(\alpha) \text{ simple}
                </me>.
                
            </p>
        </statement>
    </theorem>
    

</section>
